    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$17.5B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2024 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$2.91B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">562M</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Shares Outstanding</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(cashAndInvestments / 1000).toFixed(2)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Cash & Equivalents</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(2)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash (Debt)</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Emerson Electric generated <strong>$2.91 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2024. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, representing the pure cash profitability of the firm.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We project FCF to grow at a conservative <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% per year</strong> for the next 5 years. Emerson's transition towards automation software suggests higher future margins, supporting steady mid-single-digit to high-single-digit FCF growth as the portfolio reshapes.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate Terminal Value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>Beyond year 5, we assume the company will grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}% perpetually</strong> into the future, roughly in line with long-term global GDP and inflation. The terminal value is calculated using the Gordon Growth Model.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount back to present value</h4>
      <p>Future cash is worth less than today's cash. We discount all projected cash flows and the terminal value back to today using a <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Adjust for net debt and calculate per-share value</h4>
      <p>We add total cash (${cashAndInvestments}M) and subtract total debt (${totalDebt}M) to find the equity value. Divide by {sharesOutstanding} million shares to get the final intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Core Assumptions</h2>
  <p>Valuation is only as good as its inputs. Here are the exact numbers we used for Emerson Electric, and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">With the 10-year Treasury at 4.18%, an equity risk premium, and a modest beta typical for industrial firms, 9% represents a reasonable required return for an automation leader.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">Assumes EMR executes on its shift to a pure-play automation software & hardware company (with the NI acquisition contributing), expanding margins and FCF conversion.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">A standard perpetual growth rate that assumes EMR will mature and grow slightly faster than inflation but slower than the broader market forever.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>Projected FCF</th>
          <th>PV Factor ({(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%)</th>
          <th>Present Value</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Current (FY24)</td>
          <td>${fcf2024}M</td>
          <td>1.000</td>
          <td>-</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year}</td>
            <td>${p.fcf}M</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(3)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF}M</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Total PV of Years 1-5</td>
          <td></td>
          <td></td>
          <td>${pvPhase1}M</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE & FINAL MATH ═══ -->
  <h2>From Enterprise Value to Share Price</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Present Value of Years 1-5</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Present Value of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Enterprise Value (Core Business)</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Add: Cash & Short-Term Investments</td>
          <td>${cashAndInvestments}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Less: Total Debt</td>
          <td>-${totalDebt}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Total Equity Value</td>
          <td>${equityValue}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Shares Outstanding</td>
          <td>{sharesOutstanding}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate. Reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Because of the substantial debt load, a higher discount rate drastically reduces the per-share value.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>NI Synergies:</strong> The massive National Instruments acquisition could yield larger-than-expected cost and revenue synergies over the next few years, expanding margins beyond expectations.</li>
    <li><strong>Automation Boom:</strong> The global shift toward reshoring and factory automation could result in sustained high-single or low-double digit revenue growth, significantly outpacing the 8% FCF growth assumption.</li>
    <li><strong>Deleveraging:</strong> As Emerson pays down debt with its substantial free cash flows, the net debt drag decreases over time, moving more value to the equity holders.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Integration Risks:</strong> EMR's aggressive portfolio transformation (spinning out climate technologies, acquiring NI) brings execution risks. Failure to integrate or achieve synergies could destroy shareholder value.</li>
    <li><strong>Cyclical Downturns:</strong> Despite efforts to focus on software and higher-margin automation, Emerson is still exposed to global industrial capex cycles. A broad recession would shrink near-term FCFs.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With over $13 billion in debt, increased interest rates or a prolonged downturn could strain cash flows more severely than a peer with a clean balance sheet.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. During bubbles, P/E ratios are high; during panics, they're low. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 9% discount rate and not 8% or 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. For an established industrial firm pivoting towards high-margin automation with some cyclicality, 9% reflects an adequate premium for taking on the equity risk and the integration risk of recent acquisitions. The sensitivity table shows how values shift at 8% and 10%.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why the large negative adjustment for net cash?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Emerson Electric took on significant debt to fund recent M&A, including the National Instruments acquisition. Total debt is over $13.7 billion against just $1.5 billion in cash. When calculating the value of the <em>shares</em>, we must subtract this net debt from the total enterprise value, as debt holders have first claim on those cash flows.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

